SIMPLE: elevate
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Elevate
<hw>El"e*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>elevatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Elevated; raised aloft.</def>
<mark>[Poetic]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elevate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Elevate
<hw>El"e*vate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Elevated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Elevating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>elevatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>elevare</ets>; <ets>e</ets> +
<ets>levare</ets> to lift up, raise, akin to <ets>levis</ets> light in
weight. See <er>Levity</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring from a
lower place to a higher; to lift up; to raise; <as>as, to
<ex>elevate</ex> a weight, a flagstaff, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To raise to a higher station; to promote; <as>as, to
<ex>elevate</ex> to an office, or to a high social
position</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To raise from a depressed state; to animate; to
cheer; <as>as, to <ex>elevate</ex> the spirits</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To exalt; to ennoble; to dignify; <as>as, to
<ex>elevate</ex> the mind or character</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To raise to a higher pitch, or to a greater degree
of loudness; -- said of sounds; <as>as, to <ex>elevate</ex> the
voice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To intoxicate in a slight degree; to render
tipsy.</def> <mark>[Colloq. & Sportive]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>elevated</xex> cavaliers sent for two tubs of merry stingo.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To lessen; to detract from; to disparage.</def>
<mark>[A Latin meaning]</mark> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To elevate a piece</b></col> <fld>(Gun.)</fld>, <cd>to
raise the muzzle; to lower the breech.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To exalt; dignify; ennoble; erect; raise; hoist;
heighten; elate; cheer; flush; excite; animate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Elevated</ent>⟦br⟧
